WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:03.880
Hello, everyone.

00:00:03.880 --> 00:00:09.000
I'm very excited to be here to tell you about Keras 3, our latest release of Keras, which

00:00:09.000 --> 00:00:13.560
is a framework that you can use to do deep learning in ART.

00:00:13.560 --> 00:00:17.040
I'm going to start high level with an introduction to Keras, and then I'll talk about what's

00:00:17.040 --> 00:00:19.840
new in Keras 3.

00:00:19.840 --> 00:00:24.280
So deep learning is just one kind of machine learning, which is just one approach to building

00:00:24.280 --> 00:00:26.080
an AI system.

00:00:26.080 --> 00:00:28.139
And deep learning is not new.

00:00:28.139 --> 00:00:30.580
It's been around for over 50 years.

00:00:30.580 --> 00:00:33.259
And for most of that time, it was relatively niche.

00:00:33.259 --> 00:00:37.500
But today it's the dominant approach in a number of fields, including computer vision,

00:00:37.500 --> 00:00:42.700
speech recognition, and now with LLMs, natural language processing.

00:00:42.700 --> 00:00:47.540
And I think it's worthwhile to pause and reflect and ask, why does it seem like deep learning

00:00:47.540 --> 00:00:51.779
is outpacing all these other or other ML techniques?

00:00:51.779 --> 00:00:54.939
And there are lots and lots of ways to answer this question.

00:00:54.939 --> 00:00:57.880
I want to give three answers.

00:00:57.880 --> 00:01:01.400
The first is well articulated, I think, by this essay published a couple of years ago

00:01:01.400 --> 00:01:04.599
by Rich Sutton called The Bitter Lesson.

00:01:04.599 --> 00:01:07.000
In this, it's a short essay, you should go read it.

00:01:07.000 --> 00:01:13.080
In this essay, he reflects on the past decades of AI research and makes the observation that

00:01:13.080 --> 00:01:18.320
in the long term, because of Moore's law, it's the techniques that scale with compute

00:01:18.320 --> 00:01:19.720
that end up winning.

00:01:19.720 --> 00:01:24.919
And one of the techniques that scales the best that we know of is deep learning.

00:01:24.959 --> 00:01:30.120
So over time, as computers have gotten faster, compute has become more available and deep

00:01:30.120 --> 00:01:32.440
learning has become relevant in more contexts.

00:01:32.440 --> 00:01:38.239
And that includes both the context of supercomputers and the context of your laptops.

00:01:38.239 --> 00:01:41.040
And I think we can safely expect this trend to continue.

00:01:41.040 --> 00:01:45.120
Computers will get faster, compute will become more available, and deep learning, we'll see

00:01:45.120 --> 00:01:49.160
deep learning become relevant in more and more contexts over time.

00:01:49.160 --> 00:01:52.339
So that's one reason why deep learning is where it is today.

00:01:52.339 --> 00:01:54.599
Another reason is it's a general purpose technique.

00:01:54.599 --> 00:01:55.919
It's very versatile.

00:01:55.919 --> 00:02:00.900
You can easily apply it to all kinds of data, including text, image, audio, video, tables,

00:02:00.900 --> 00:02:03.300
time series, graphs.

00:02:03.300 --> 00:02:07.680
And you can apply it to all kinds of tasks, not just classification and regression, but

00:02:07.680 --> 00:02:12.960
also the many, many flavors of content generation.

00:02:12.960 --> 00:02:16.720
And the third reason is that deep learning is forgiving and reliable.

00:02:16.720 --> 00:02:22.479
And this is where frameworks like Keras come in, because they help make it so.

00:02:22.479 --> 00:02:27.199
You can think of Keras as a kit for doing deep learning, kind of like a Marble Run toy

00:02:27.199 --> 00:02:28.199
set.

00:02:28.199 --> 00:02:31.919
If you haven't played with one of these before, when you first get it and open the box, it's

00:02:31.919 --> 00:02:32.919
a little bit overwhelming.

00:02:32.919 --> 00:02:38.639
There are so many parts and some of them are truly complicated, or they seem complicated.

00:02:38.639 --> 00:02:42.839
But pretty quickly you figure out that all these parts compose with each other via a

00:02:42.839 --> 00:02:43.839
very simple interface.

00:02:43.839 --> 00:02:45.360
They just stack right on top of each other.

00:02:45.360 --> 00:02:47.119
It's plug and play.

00:02:47.119 --> 00:02:50.639
And when you are composing these parts together, what you're doing is you're creating a path

00:02:50.720 --> 00:02:53.000
for marbles to flow through.

00:02:53.000 --> 00:02:54.000
And Keras is like this.

00:02:54.000 --> 00:02:58.960
It has a lot of parts, but they all compose with each other very nicely.

00:02:58.960 --> 00:03:02.199
And when you're composing them, you're creating a path for data to go through.

00:03:02.199 --> 00:03:05.179
And because everything works so seamlessly, the whole thing feels spi.

00:03:05.179 --> 00:03:09.919
It's fun to design your models and build them, and it's fun to feed them data and watch them

00:03:09.919 --> 00:03:11.839
learn.

00:03:11.839 --> 00:03:13.440
So what's in the kit?

00:03:13.440 --> 00:03:15.440
Keras comes with over 100 built-in layers.

00:03:15.440 --> 00:03:18.479
These are the things that you'll use to actually build your model.

00:03:18.479 --> 00:03:21.320
It also has a lot of things that go outside the model.

00:03:21.320 --> 00:03:26.000
You have metrics to track model performance during training, loss functions and optimizers

00:03:26.000 --> 00:03:31.479
which you'll use to actually train your model, data loading utilities to help you work with

00:03:31.479 --> 00:03:36.639
data that doesn't fit in memory, and a family of operations which I'll talk about later.

00:03:36.639 --> 00:03:42.360
And all these pieces fit together in a high-level training API where you just call fit.

00:03:42.360 --> 00:03:45.600
To illustrate how all these pieces fit together, I'm going to walk through the Hello World

00:03:45.600 --> 00:03:50.240
of Deep Learning, which is based on the MNIST image dataset of handwritten digits that

00:03:50.240 --> 00:03:52.059
look like this.

00:03:52.059 --> 00:03:56.240
One of the things you can do in a dataset is build a classifier.

00:03:56.240 --> 00:03:59.559
Given an image, predict what digit is it.

00:03:59.559 --> 00:04:03.000
The way you would do this in Keras is you would start by creating an input object where

00:04:03.000 --> 00:04:08.000
you specify the shape, and then you take that input object and you pipe it through a couple

00:04:08.000 --> 00:04:12.639
of layers to get back an output object.

00:04:12.679 --> 00:04:16.720
And once you have your input and your output, you have all you need to create your model,

00:04:16.720 --> 00:04:19.279
and you have a model.

00:04:19.279 --> 00:04:22.579
One of the things you can do with a model is print it, where you get this colorful summary

00:04:22.579 --> 00:04:24.899
table showing you what's in there.

00:04:24.899 --> 00:04:30.239
You can also plot it to see a flowchart of the path your data will take through the model.

00:04:30.239 --> 00:04:35.220
You can also plot it as a not-so-simple flowchart full of annotations.

00:04:35.220 --> 00:04:40.359
And then once you've created your model and you're ready to train it, this is a two-step

00:04:40.359 --> 00:04:41.359
process.

00:04:41.359 --> 00:04:46.760
You call compile, where you specify the loss function, the optimizer, and the metrics.

00:04:46.760 --> 00:04:52.519
And then you call fit with your dataset, and your model starts learning.

00:04:52.519 --> 00:04:57.079
Now this example model that I'm showing here is the simplest practical model you could

00:04:57.079 --> 00:04:58.079
make.

00:04:58.079 --> 00:05:03.739
It only has one trainable layer, it has no fancy tricks, but this remarkably simple model

00:05:03.739 --> 00:05:08.880
already trains to 92% accuracy on the MNIST image dataset.

00:05:08.880 --> 00:05:12.880
And this is what I mean when I say that deep learning is forgiving, because there are plenty

00:05:12.880 --> 00:05:18.500
of contexts I can think of where 92% accuracy is already plenty useful.

00:05:18.500 --> 00:05:23.619
And you don't have to be a deep learning expert to walk away with a model that's useful.

00:05:23.619 --> 00:05:25.160
But of course we can get better.

00:05:25.160 --> 00:05:29.679
One of the things that Keras makes easy is experimenting with different model architectures.

00:05:29.679 --> 00:05:33.320
So let's say we insert one additional dense layer into this model.

00:05:33.320 --> 00:05:36.679
Now we get up to 97% accuracy.

00:05:36.679 --> 00:05:41.119
Create a 2D convolutional layer in front of that, and you get to 98% accuracy.

00:05:41.119 --> 00:05:45.380
Make that two 2D convolutional layers, and you get to 99% accuracy.

00:05:45.380 --> 00:05:49.200
And this is pretty close to state-of-the-art for MNIST.

00:05:49.200 --> 00:05:53.119
If you're wondering what all this looks like when you're working interactively in the IDE,

00:05:53.119 --> 00:05:56.959
you get this colorful progress bar, and you also have a live metrics viewer where you

00:05:56.959 --> 00:05:59.440
can see your model learn in real time.

00:05:59.440 --> 00:06:03.019
And I think it's kind of fun to watch, it's a little bit like watching marbles go down

00:06:03.019 --> 00:06:05.079
a marble run.

00:06:06.079 --> 00:06:10.679
Okay, so that gives you a flavor for what first steps with Keras looks like.

00:06:10.679 --> 00:06:15.440
There is a lot of effort to make sure there is a smooth initial experience, and that might

00:06:15.440 --> 00:06:18.779
give you the impression that Keras is like a set of training wheels, where it's really

00:06:18.779 --> 00:06:22.880
helpful at first but will become constraining later on.

00:06:22.880 --> 00:06:24.279
But that's not the case.

00:06:24.279 --> 00:06:29.880
Keras is a framework that you can continue to use as your skills and your expertise develops.

00:06:29.880 --> 00:06:33.320
And in my opinion, where Keras truly shines is in research environments, when you're trying

00:06:33.320 --> 00:06:37.799
to do something new and custom because of how flexible the API is there.

00:06:37.799 --> 00:06:42.239
And that's because Keras ultimately has its roots in research.

00:06:42.239 --> 00:06:47.000
The way Keras can accommodate these different user profiles is through this idea that's

00:06:47.000 --> 00:06:53.359
baked into the API called progressive disclosure of complexity, which is another way of saying

00:06:53.359 --> 00:06:55.519
there is no one true way to do anything.

00:06:55.519 --> 00:07:00.679
For any given task, Keras offers multiple ways to do it, each of them striking a different

00:07:00.679 --> 00:07:07.160
point in the balance between flexibility and exposed complexity.

00:07:07.160 --> 00:07:12.920
So I can't illustrate all the ways that this is true in the API, the API surface is large,

00:07:12.920 --> 00:07:15.399
but to illustrate the point, I want to show just one.

00:07:15.399 --> 00:07:20.079
So let's say you want to create a custom layer, Keras comes with 100 layers, but none of them

00:07:20.079 --> 00:07:22.720
do exactly what you want, you want to make your own.

00:07:22.720 --> 00:07:27.079
The simplest way to do this is to call layer lambda and pass in a function there that takes

00:07:27.079 --> 00:07:32.320
a tensor, and you can do whatever work you want on that tensor in that function.

00:07:32.320 --> 00:07:36.000
Another way is to use another model as a layer.

00:07:36.000 --> 00:07:41.359
So models are layers too, which means that you can compose layers both sequentially and

00:07:41.359 --> 00:07:44.279
recursively.

00:07:44.279 --> 00:07:47.920
The next step up in complexity is to subclass the base layer class.

00:07:47.920 --> 00:07:51.799
And here you can implement some or all of the methods that are called at different points

00:07:51.799 --> 00:07:53.920
in the layer's lifecycle.

00:07:53.920 --> 00:07:59.760
And a custom layer created in this way has identical semantics to the built-in layers.

00:07:59.760 --> 00:08:03.559
And as your code base grows, you can use inheritance to help manage your code.

00:08:03.559 --> 00:08:08.720
So you can subclass not just the base layer class, but also other built-in layers and

00:08:08.720 --> 00:08:11.899
other custom layers.

00:08:11.899 --> 00:08:17.859
And this subclassing API exists not just for layers, but for all the object types that

00:08:17.920 --> 00:08:23.459
you might work with in Keras, including training callbacks, metrics, learning rate schedules,

00:08:23.459 --> 00:08:27.100
and so on.

00:08:27.100 --> 00:08:32.780
For R users, along this path of progressive disclosure of complexity is the fact that

00:08:32.780 --> 00:08:37.099
under the hood, Keras in R is implemented using reticulate.

00:08:37.099 --> 00:08:44.099
And reticulate is an R package that embeds Python in R. What this means is that everything

00:08:44.099 --> 00:08:51.739
available in Python is also available in R. So you can choose to use Keras in R or

00:08:51.739 --> 00:08:57.140
Keras — you can choose to use Keras from R or Keras from Python, and because of reticulate,

00:08:57.140 --> 00:09:02.460
that choice is simply a matter of preference for language syntax and development environment.

00:09:02.460 --> 00:09:06.580
You don't have to worry about one interface getting out of sync with the other, or one

00:09:06.580 --> 00:09:11.419
having more features than the other, or one being faster than the other, because when

00:09:11.419 --> 00:09:17.539
you're training your model, it's literally the same exact code that's running.

00:09:17.539 --> 00:09:21.700
Reticulate itself has had a steady stream of updates over the past few years.

00:09:21.700 --> 00:09:26.059
There's improved error tracebacks, improved autocomplete, improved support for operators

00:09:26.059 --> 00:09:31.739
and generics, and probably most exciting of all, updated Python environment and discovery

00:09:31.739 --> 00:09:32.739
tools.

00:09:32.739 --> 00:09:38.659
Quick aside, I've heard from multiple people tell me that they work primarily in Python,

00:09:38.659 --> 00:09:44.460
but they use Reticulate to set up their Python environments, which I just think is so neat.

00:09:44.460 --> 00:09:49.820
Back to Keras 3, what's new in Keras 3?

00:09:49.820 --> 00:09:55.419
The biggest thing to know is the return of multi-backend support, and that comes with

00:09:55.419 --> 00:10:00.940
a set of new features that let you write backend agnostic code.

00:10:00.940 --> 00:10:06.299
A backend is something that Keras uses to compute gradients and to interface with a

00:10:06.299 --> 00:10:07.820
GPU.

00:10:07.820 --> 00:10:12.140
And for most of its life, up to about three years ago, Keras supported multiple backends,

00:10:12.140 --> 00:10:15.260
including TensorFlow, Theano, MXNet, and CNTKit.

00:10:15.260 --> 00:10:21.219
And then over time, those last three were retired, and three years ago, TensorFlow became

00:10:21.219 --> 00:10:27.299
the only supported backend when Keras became an official part of the TensorFlow project.

00:10:27.299 --> 00:10:33.080
Now with Keras 3, Keras is once again a standalone package that's not part of TensorFlow.

00:10:33.080 --> 00:10:37.479
When you first load the package, you can call use-backend with the name of your backend,

00:10:37.479 --> 00:10:41.679
and the supported backends today are Jaxx, PyTorch, and TensorFlow.

00:10:41.679 --> 00:10:46.559
You can also use NumPy in inference-only mode, and there's some work to add MLX as a backend

00:10:46.559 --> 00:10:49.880
ongoing.

00:10:49.880 --> 00:10:54.640
The benefits of multi-backend support are that it lets you write future-proof code.

00:10:54.640 --> 00:10:59.400
The high-level Keras API insulates you a little bit from some of the churn in the low-level

00:10:59.400 --> 00:11:01.200
framework space.

00:11:01.200 --> 00:11:05.320
You can easily switch backends at any time in a project, which means that if you encounter

00:11:05.320 --> 00:11:09.479
a bug with one backend, you can just sidestep it by switching to another.

00:11:09.479 --> 00:11:12.760
And more generally, it enables workflows where you can take advantage of the best that each

00:11:12.760 --> 00:11:14.400
backend has to offer.

00:11:14.400 --> 00:11:18.520
So for example, you can develop your model with Torch as your backend, which gives you

00:11:18.520 --> 00:11:20.440
a nice interactive experience.

00:11:20.440 --> 00:11:25.039
And then you can switch to Jaxx to train it, which will give you the fastest performance

00:11:25.039 --> 00:11:26.359
typically.

00:11:26.359 --> 00:11:29.840
And then when you're getting ready to deploy, you can switch to TensorFlow, which has the

00:11:29.840 --> 00:11:33.440
most mature deployment options.

00:11:33.440 --> 00:11:38.080
One of the things that makes this possible is the new saving and loading API that comes

00:11:38.080 --> 00:11:41.080
with a new backend agnostic file format.

00:11:41.080 --> 00:11:46.280
So say you train your model with Jaxx, you can then save that to a file with the .keras

00:11:46.280 --> 00:11:50.640
extension, and then in a different R session with a different backend, the TensorFlow backend,

00:11:50.640 --> 00:11:55.599
you can load that model, and you've effectively converted your Jaxx model to a TensorFlow

00:11:55.599 --> 00:11:56.859
model.

00:11:56.859 --> 00:12:01.340
One reason you might want to do this is because you are getting ready to deploy.

00:12:01.340 --> 00:12:06.500
And one of the easiest ways to deploy a Keras model is to connect.

00:12:06.500 --> 00:12:15.659
Connect recently gained the ability to serve Keras 3 models using TensorFlow serving, which

00:12:15.659 --> 00:12:21.140
gives you access to a scalable concurrent serving with no R or Python runtime, with

00:12:21.140 --> 00:12:26.539
just these two function calls.

00:12:27.219 --> 00:12:31.340
Another thing that comes with the multibackend support in Keras is the Ops family.

00:12:31.340 --> 00:12:38.099
This is a suite of 200 lower level functions for working with multidimensional arrays.

00:12:38.099 --> 00:12:42.059
These functions all work the same regardless of if you're working with TensorFlow, Torch

00:12:42.059 --> 00:12:47.159
or Jaxx tensors, if you're working in eager mode or in graph mode, and you can use them

00:12:47.159 --> 00:12:49.979
to write backend agnostic code.

00:12:49.979 --> 00:12:54.580
You can use these anywhere where you operate with tensors, including at the top level REPL,

00:12:54.580 --> 00:12:57.859
and custom layers, custom losses, custom metrics, and so on.

00:12:57.859 --> 00:13:01.140
You can also use them as standalone layers.

00:13:01.140 --> 00:13:04.940
The Ops API surface aims to be comprehensive.

00:13:04.940 --> 00:13:11.820
It includes the NumPy API, the TFNN API, a set of linear algebra operations, image operations

00:13:11.820 --> 00:13:14.659
and more.

00:13:14.659 --> 00:13:18.780
I think our users in particular are going to appreciate the Ops family because it provides

00:13:18.780 --> 00:13:24.059
a more ergonomic alternative to using the backend through reticulate.

00:13:24.059 --> 00:13:28.859
You get things like consistent one-based indexing, automatic coercion of arguments,

00:13:28.859 --> 00:13:35.140
and best of all, built-in R documentation with lots and lots of R examples.

00:13:35.140 --> 00:13:39.619
Another reason why I think our users will like it is a little more abstract, but all

00:13:39.619 --> 00:13:42.280
the functions are pure, so they have no side effects.

00:13:42.280 --> 00:13:44.820
That makes for a much more consistent experience.

00:13:44.820 --> 00:13:49.940
It encourages experimentation at the REPL, and it aligns better with the mental model

00:13:49.940 --> 00:13:53.900
that R encourages.

00:13:53.900 --> 00:13:57.539
There's a lot of other stuff that's new in Keras 3 that I don't have time to cover in

00:13:57.539 --> 00:14:00.299
detail, but I just want to mention briefly.

00:14:00.299 --> 00:14:04.380
There's the subclassing API, which I showed a little bit of earlier.

00:14:04.380 --> 00:14:08.820
There's a whole new API for building models that ingest tabular data, things like data

00:14:08.820 --> 00:14:09.820
frames.

00:14:09.820 --> 00:14:11.380
That's very nice.

00:14:11.380 --> 00:14:16.780
There's a new API for generating random numbers inside your model that has support for usage

00:14:16.780 --> 00:14:21.859
in pure functions by passing a C generator.

00:14:21.859 --> 00:14:26.979
There's a new API for doing distributed training that now has support not just for data parallelism,

00:14:26.979 --> 00:14:30.979
but also model parallelism.

00:14:30.979 --> 00:14:34.419
There's support for quantizing models, which is important when you're dealing with very,

00:14:34.419 --> 00:14:37.500
very large models, like large language models.

00:14:37.500 --> 00:14:41.700
And there is expanded entry points for customizing training.

00:14:41.700 --> 00:14:46.340
We put in custom training steps or custom training loops.

00:14:46.340 --> 00:14:50.820
To learn more, please visit keras3.posit.co.

00:14:50.820 --> 00:14:55.619
There you'll find three kinds of content, guides, examples, and references.

00:14:55.619 --> 00:14:59.859
Guides are long-form explanations of Keras concepts.

00:14:59.859 --> 00:15:05.020
Examples demonstrate Keras use to solve a particular task.

00:15:05.020 --> 00:15:08.820
And the reference section comprehensively documents all of the functions and arguments

00:15:08.820 --> 00:15:15.780
and classes and methods and attributes, including lots of R examples.

00:15:15.780 --> 00:15:20.219
And finally, to learn more about deep learning, please check out the second edition of Deep

00:15:20.219 --> 00:15:24.940
Learning with R. Even though this book was written for Keras 2, it is still very much

00:15:24.940 --> 00:15:31.820
relevant for Keras 3, and it is still the best way to get started with deep learning.

00:15:31.820 --> 00:15:33.820
Thank you very much.

00:15:34.020 --> 00:15:36.020
Spelt it.

00:15:36.020 --> 00:15:38.020
All right.

00:15:38.020 --> 00:15:40.020
Thank you.

00:15:40.020 --> 00:15:44.020
People are already, like, wondering where to get your slides.

00:15:44.020 --> 00:15:46.020
Where do I get my slides?

00:15:46.020 --> 00:15:48.020
Now, where will they get your slides?

00:15:48.020 --> 00:15:50.020
Oh, I can put them up on my GitHub.

00:15:50.020 --> 00:15:52.020
I don't have a link yet, because I haven't made that public.

00:15:52.020 --> 00:15:54.020
But I can put them up on my GitHub.

00:15:54.020 --> 00:15:56.020
I can put them up on my GitHub.

00:15:56.020 --> 00:15:58.020
I can put them up on my GitHub.

00:15:58.020 --> 00:16:00.020
I can put them up on my GitHub.

00:16:00.020 --> 00:16:02.020
I can put them up on my GitHub.

00:16:02.219 --> 00:16:04.219
I can't make them public, but I will.

00:16:04.219 --> 00:16:06.219
There is interest.

00:16:06.219 --> 00:16:08.219
You bet.

