The next one, I swear it is not my question, but does Keras play nicely with tidy models?

00:16:14.219 --> 00:16:16.219
Yes.

00:16:16.219 --> 00:16:18.219
I believe so.

00:16:18.219 --> 00:16:22.219
I don't think it's been updated for Keras 3 yet, but it will be shortly.

00:16:22.219 --> 00:16:24.219
That's not a habit, do you?

00:16:24.219 --> 00:16:26.219
Okay.

00:16:26.219 --> 00:16:28.219
We got...

00:16:28.219 --> 00:16:30.219
Questions are coming.

00:16:30.419 --> 00:16:32.419
Questions are coming.

00:16:32.419 --> 00:16:34.419
Well done, Rym.

00:16:34.419 --> 00:16:36.419
Okay.

00:16:36.419 --> 00:16:40.419
How much work will it be rewriting my old Keras code to Keras 3?

00:16:40.419 --> 00:16:44.419
That depends on how much custom stuff you did that's backend-specific.

00:16:44.419 --> 00:16:49.419
So if you were mostly using the high-level layer functions

00:16:49.419 --> 00:16:52.419
and the built-in losses and metrics and optimizers,

00:16:52.419 --> 00:16:54.419
then there's very little work for you to do.

00:16:54.419 --> 00:16:56.419
It might even work out of the box.

00:16:56.619 --> 00:17:00.619
But if you were writing custom loss functions

00:17:00.619 --> 00:17:02.619
where you're using the TensorFlow API directly,

00:17:02.619 --> 00:17:04.619
you're going to have to translate that to using the ops family.

00:17:04.619 --> 00:17:06.619
And then more generally,

00:17:06.619 --> 00:17:09.619
if you're doing a lot of fancy serialization,

00:17:09.619 --> 00:17:11.619
there's a lot of...

00:17:11.619 --> 00:17:14.619
The saving and serialization API is quite comprehensive now

00:17:14.619 --> 00:17:16.619
and very different than before.

00:17:16.619 --> 00:17:20.619
It wouldn't be 2024 without an LLM question.

00:17:20.619 --> 00:17:22.619
Of course.

00:17:22.619 --> 00:17:25.619
Can Keras be used to fine-tune LLMs?

00:17:25.819 --> 00:17:27.819
Yes, it can.

00:17:27.819 --> 00:17:29.819
I did not include that in my talk,

00:17:29.819 --> 00:17:31.819
but there is a Keras NLP package

00:17:31.819 --> 00:17:33.819
which you can use to articulate,

00:17:33.819 --> 00:17:36.819
and there is support for either training from scratch

00:17:36.819 --> 00:17:39.819
if you have the resources, or fine-tune.

00:17:39.819 --> 00:17:41.819
Excellent.

00:17:41.819 --> 00:17:45.819
This goes into maybe slightly the other direction.

00:17:45.819 --> 00:17:49.819
Why should a data scientist working exclusively with tabular data

00:17:49.819 --> 00:17:51.819
use deep learning through Keras

00:17:51.819 --> 00:17:54.819
instead of regression or tree-based approaches?

00:17:55.020 --> 00:17:58.020
Yes, that is an excellent question.

00:17:58.020 --> 00:18:02.020
So, you don't have to switch to deep learning.

00:18:02.020 --> 00:18:04.020
Deep learning is like duct tape,

00:18:04.020 --> 00:18:07.020
so it's not always the best solution for the tool,

00:18:07.020 --> 00:18:10.020
but more often than not, it's good enough.

00:18:10.020 --> 00:18:12.020
So that's my answer.

00:18:13.020 --> 00:18:15.020
Nice analogy.

00:18:15.020 --> 00:18:18.020
Somebody asks if there are any concerns

00:18:18.020 --> 00:18:20.020
